Dae,

There is an ambiguity in the current domain scheme, which tends to be
used both for naming (its purpose, I guess) and for addressing. If
adressing is what you want, the inclusion of routing -- or geographic
-- information may be thought of as desirable; one way is to base the
routing on the country name when there is a single entry point per
country. If you look at the routing tables in a number of sites -- or
if you look at the content of the DNS for a number of European
countries, you will see that this is the case.

If on the other hand you regard the naming function, the top level
domains are supposed to reflect the ``scope'' of a name, i.e. the
portion of the ``world'' into which this name is well known +
guaranteed unique. Some names are only valid within a specific
organizational range, some others have a limited geographical scope,
some are world wide unique -- not so many, probably.

To give a counter example to your assertion that ``(you) see nothing to
refute my suspicion that organization codes will grow..'', I can give
the example of CERN, a truly international organization, founded by an
international treaty etc, which declined an invitation to be registered
as ``cern.org'', and choose ``cern.ch'' instead -- as they are located in Geneva.

Christian Huitema

